total volume that it occupies

00:05:12.069 --> 00:05:15.110
is not equal to the total volume of
the candy because there's gaps in it.

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:15.760
There's air.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:17.250
There's free space.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:21.450
So have any of you ever entered to
count the jelly beans in a jar contest?

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:23.890
So the reason that you
can't win-- well, there

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:25.830
are several reasons
why it's hard to win.

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:27.760
One is you have to know
the volume of the jar.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:28.960
You're not allowed to weigh the jar.

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:30.450
If you weigh the jar
you could always win.

00:05:30.450 --> 00:05:32.380
Because you would weigh the jar
and then you would weigh the candy.

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:33.184
And you would win.

00:05:33.184 --> 00:05:34.600
But you're not allowed to do that.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.810
And so what you have to do is estimate
how much free space there is in the jar

00:05:37.810 --> 00:05:39.750
because the jar is not
densely packed with candy.

00:05:39.750 --> 00:05:41.624
And it turns out there's
a rule of thumb that

00:05:41.624 --> 00:05:44.470
is very important in this regard,
which is that it turns out

00:05:44.470 --> 00:05:47.460
that if the candy were spheres,
they were spherical objects,

00:05:47.460 --> 00:05:51.100
then there's a number, which is
64%, which is the volume of space

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:52.390
that the candy occupies.

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:54.660
So 36% of it is free space.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:59.180
If it's M&amp;Ms, then it
turns out it's about 70%.

00:05:59.180 --> 00:06:01.637
So somewhere around 30%
of it is free space.

00:06:01.637 --> 00:06:03.720
