00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:30.431
So we want to make sure that
this-- you'll let us know.

00:11:30.431 --> 00:11:31.010
OK.

00:11:31.010 --> 00:11:34.000
So the first dish is going to be a foam.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.610
To me, a foam in scientific
terms in the kitchen

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:41.730
means a fancy word that you can use for
a sauce and charge more money for it.

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:46.400
It's called a foam,
easily five more dollars.

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:48.130
That's the science behind it for us.

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.270
So it's actually math.

00:11:50.270 --> 00:11:51.610
This isn't a math lecture.

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:52.110
No.

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:52.490
OK.

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:53.070
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: Economics.

00:11:53.070 --> 00:11:53.660
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: It's not.

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:54.310
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: Economics.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:55.601
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: Wrong class.

00:11:55.601 --> 00:11:58.070
You guys are in the wrong class Yeah.

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:01.414
How to take yogurt and turn
it into a lot of money.

00:12:01.414 --> 00:12:02.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:07.200
For us, a foam, I think the
easiest way to understand

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:11.460
it is trapping a gas
inside a liquid or a solid.

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:17.980
So inside this thing is some yogurt,
some buttermilk, some roasted garlic,

00:12:17.980 --> 00:12:20.880
and a little bit of salt.
And then this is NO2.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:24.290
You put that in, the gas goes in.

00:12:24.290 --> 00:12:27.590
And then when we shake it up and
put it out, you get the foam.

00:12:27.590 --> 00:12:30.170
And so you're saying, well,
why would you do that?

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:33.370
Why would you do that
for this cucumber salad?

00:12:33.370 --> 00:12:37.450
This dish is based on a tzatziki,
a normal dish of cucumber,

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:41.260
yogurt, usually some lemon, some zaatar,
a delicious dish, one of my favorites.

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:44.200
But we take dishes like
that and we try and add

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:46.575
a little bit of that creative
process or creativity to it

00:12:46.575 --> 00:12:48.616
and figure out a way to
make it a little bit more

00:12:48.616 --> 00:12:49.930
unique, a little bit different.

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:54.490
And so with this one, we're
adding the NO2, creating the foam.

00:12:54.490 --> 00:12:56.240
And that wasn't going
to be the end of it.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:57.823
And then we have to freeze everything.

00:12:57.823 --> 00:13:00.610
I mean now this stuff
is available to us too.

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:03.490
So this is at Whole Foods I
think, in the frozen food section.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:09.106
You can buy liquid nitrogen.
And so if you take yogurt

00:13:09.106 --> 00:13:10.980
and you just drop it in
to the nitrogen, it's

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:12.430
going to freeze and
turn into an ice cube.

00:13:12.430 --> 00:13:14.950
And then when you put it into your
mouth, it's going to crack your teeth.

00:13:14.950 --> 00:13:18.210
And then that yogurt that you charged
all that money for, you're now

00:13:18.210 --> 00:13:21.390
going to get sued, to pay somebody
back for the tooth that you just broke.

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:24.190
So it's actually not
a good way to do that.

00:13:24.190 --> 00:13:26.380
And so we had to figure
out a way to not get

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:29.302
sued when we put frozen
yogurt in front of people,

00:13:29.302 --> 00:13:30.510
without cracking their teeth.

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:32.480
And so we add the gas to it.

00:13:32.480 --> 00:13:34.010
It turned it into a foam.

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:36.100
We're going to extract the
foam into the nitrogen.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:38.558
And that's going to be the
dressing for the cucumber salad.

00:13:38.558 --> 00:13:40.250
So the rest of it is pretty basic.

00:13:40.250 --> 00:13:41.990
We've got some cucumbers here.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:45.890
Been vacuum packed to kind of take
some of that atmosphere out of it.

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:48.460
Is that pretty accurate?

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:51.932
Take some of the atmosphere
out of it, or not.

00:13:51.932 --> 00:13:55.800
It sounded fancy, right?

00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:58.252
So this is just a cucumber
that's been vacuum packed

00:13:58.252 --> 00:13:59.710
with a little bit of its own juice.

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:00.668
I'm going to cut it up.

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:04.920
This is oblique.

00:14:04.920 --> 00:14:06.658
Did you know that word, oblique?

00:14:06.658 --> 00:14:08.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:08.060 --> 00:14:11.060
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: Well, the cool thing
is when you compress the cucumber,

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:12.330
it changes the structure of it.

00:14:12.330 --> 00:14:13.900
It actually gives it
a different texture.

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:14.750
It's not as crisp.

00:14:14.750 --> 00:14:16.570
But it actually has-- it's still crisp.

00:14:16.570 --> 00:14:17.910
But it still has a chew.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:19.660
And it's actually really delicious.

00:14:19.660 --> 00:14:23.100
It compresses the cell
walls of the vegetable

00:14:23.100 --> 00:14:25.990
and actually almost juices itself.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:29.070
When you cut into it, it starts
to kind of ooze out a little bit.

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:31.564
And so it just tastes more
like cucumber somehow.

00:14:31.564 --> 00:14:33.480
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: I
think it just looks cool.

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:34.540
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: It looks cool too.

00:14:34.540 --> 00:14:35.360
It changes the color.

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:35.650
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: Yeah.

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:37.880
Who's ever seen a cucumber
that looks this color?

00:14:37.880 --> 00:14:38.880
Don't look at the shape.

00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:39.379
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:39.379 --> 00:14:40.120
This-- come on.

00:14:40.120 --> 00:14:43.200
This is Harvard.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.820
So there's lemon oil inside the
bowl, a little bit of lemon juice.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:49.730
We're going to add some
acid to it, to season it.

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:53.500
A little bit of salt over
here, I've got some flake salt.

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:57.320
And again, this is just a
basic, simple cucumber salad

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:00.450
you can make at home if you've got
liquid nitrogen, and NO2, and all

00:15:00.450 --> 00:15:04.760
that stuff sitting
around in the cabinet,

00:15:04.760 --> 00:15:09.340
and a really great description
of what emulsions and foams are.

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:12.800
If you have that too in your head,
then you can put this together at home.

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:14.946
So these are our cucumbers.

00:15:14.946 --> 00:15:17.820
It's seasoned a little bit of lemon
oil, some lemon juice, some salt,

00:15:17.820 --> 00:15:18.660
and some zaatar.

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:21.090
So it's got that Middle Eastern
sort of flavor going on.

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:28.200
And then I'm going to put a couple
of these into a bowl, like this.

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:34.020
This bowl I actually made
in the back with some clay

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:37.160
that we took out of the
ground, underneath the school.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:41.250
Oh, we went away to Williams-Somoma
and actually bought then.

00:15:41.250 --> 00:15:44.910
And then here, I've got
some charred shallots.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:50.380
And these are just shallots that I stuck
onto a cast iron pan, charred slightly.

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:54.600
And then basically just vacuum packed
them with a little bit of vinegar.

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:57.580
And so it's like a quick pickle.

00:15:57.580 --> 00:15:58.960
Do you know this word, quickle?

00:15:58.960 --> 00:16:00.018
Have you heard that?

00:16:00.018 --> 00:16:00.994
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:00.994 --> 00:16:01.970
No.

00:16:01.970 --> 00:16:03.960
This is a quickle.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.814
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: It's Webster's
2016 word of the year.

00:16:06.814 --> 00:16:08.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:10.860
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: And so
if you look up quickle,

00:16:10.860 --> 00:16:14.170
you might not find it anywhere.

00:16:14.170 --> 00:16:16.650
And the last thing is our foam.

00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:21.128
So the foam, like I said, I've got
nitrogen here, liquid nitrogen here.

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:27.955
And so basically because--

00:16:30.159 --> 00:16:31.450
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: Oop, my fault.

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:34.140
MICHAEL VOLTAGGIO: A
little bit more salt.

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:37.152
You know, the foam, the gas that's
been trapped inside the liquid

00:16:37.152 --> 00:16:39.360
or the solid-- in this case,
it's yogurt, buttermilk,

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:42.620
a little bit of lemon juice,
some salt, some roasted garlic.

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:44.930
We're going to extract
it into the nitrogen

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:47.039
so that it's airy and light and fluffy.

00:16:47.039 --> 00:16:48.830
So that when we put it
onto the plate, it's

00:16:48.830 --> 00:16:51.349
not just frozen ice cubes of
yogurt that break your teeth.

00:16:51.349 --> 00:16:54.390
And I get sued and I don't get invited
back to talk about food at Harvard

00:16:54.390 --> 00:16:55.600
anymore.

00:16:55.600 --> 00:16:59.222
So basically, right
here we've got our foam.

00:16:59.222 --> 00:17:00.290
We'll just do this.

00:17:04.749 --> 00:17:06.790
We're going to get a little
bit more air into it.

00:17:06.790 --> 00:17:08.470
How much of that is on my face already?

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:08.859
Not much.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:10.069
BRYAN VOLTAGGIO: Oh, just a little bit.

00:17:10.069 --> 00:17:11.140
Here, let me get you.

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:12.079
There you go.

